# VDP & Display Registers

## Purpose
Explain the Video Display Processor registers for the Amiga and Genesis so you can lay out sprites, planes, palettes, and DMA channels without guessing register offsets.

## Key Registers (Amiga)
- `BPLCON0/1/2`: Define bitplane depth, sprite enabling, and playfield priority.
- `DIWSTRT/DIWSTOP`: Bounds of the active display window; note the typical overscan values for OCS/ECS vs. AGA.
- `COP1L/2`, `COPJMP1/2`: Copper list pointers; document copper wait instructions, how to nest jumps, and the even-alignment requirement.
- `BPL1PTH/BPL2PTH` (and following bitplane pointers): 32-bit pointer registers; mention the `even` alignment and how to spread bitplanes across banks.
- `SPRITE DATA` and `SPRITE CONTROL` registers: show address ranges near `$00DFF1C0`.

## Key Registers (Genesis)
- `VDP Data/Control`: Main command registers; include the control word format (bit 15/14 for type, bits 13-0 for address).
- `VRAM`, `CRAM`, `VSRAM` ports: Outline access patterns and timing constraints (e.g., wait states) and note how writes must be paired with control register updates.
- `H/V Counter`: Use for horizontal/vertical sync monitoring and generating interrupts; mention that VBlank occurs at `INT 10h`.
- `Interrupt Control`: Show how VBlank and HBlank interrupt bits map to Genesis IRQs and how they tie into DMA transfers for sound/VDP updates.

## Best Practices
- Keep sprite/plane data aligned to 8-byte boundaries; mention `DMA = 1` vs. `DMA = 2` usage in comments.
- Document which Denise registers are touched by copper lists vs. general CPU writes to avoid contention.
- Include register tables that call out which chips (Denise, Paula, Genesis VDP) own each address and how customizing palettes/bitplanes influences the VDP state.
- Document the VRAM layout per platform and keep copies of typical initialization sequences (`init-vdp.s`) in `assets/vdp/`.
- When referencing new VDP helper scripts, add their names under `games/genesis/`/`games/m68k/` directories so the tour highlights them.
